Data Understanding

1. Classification Label

  • Churn - Whether the customer churned or not (Yes, No)

2. Services Definition

  • PhoneService - whether the customer has a phone service or not (Yes,No)
  • MultipleLines - whether the customer has a multiple line or not (Yes, No, No phone service)
  • InternetService - type of internet service the customer has (DSL, Fiber Optic, No)
  • OnlineSecurity - whether the customer has a online security or not (Yes, No)
  • OnlineBackup - whether the customer has a online backup or not (Yes, No)
  • DeviceProtection - whether the customer has a device protection or not (Yes, No)
  • TechSupport - whether the customer has a tech support or not (Yes,No)
  • StreamingTV - whether the customer has a streaming TV (Yes,No)
  • StreamingMovies - whether the customer has a streaming movies (Yes,No)

3. Customer Account Information

  • Tenure - how long customer has stayed in company
  • Contract - type of contract customer has (Month-to-Month, One Year, Two Year)
  • PaperlessBilling - whether the customer has a paperless billing (Yes,No)
  • PaymentMethod - payment method use by customer (Electronic check, Mailed check, Bank transfer (automatic), Credit card (automatic))
  • MonthlyCharges - amount charged to the customer monthly
  • TotalCharges - the total amount charge to the customer

4. Customer Demographic Info

  • CustomerID - Unique value for each customer
  • gender - type of gender customer has (Male,Female)
  • SeniorCitizen - whether the customer is a senior citizen (Yes,No)
  • Partner - whether the customer has a partner or not (Yes, No)
  • Dependents - whether the customer has a dependents or not (Yes,No)

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

KPIs to Calculate

  • Monthly Recurring Revenue (MRR) = sum(MonthlyCharges) for active subscribers

  • Average Order Value (AOV) = TotalCharges.mean()

  • Churn Rate = (Churned Customers / Total Customers) * 100

  • Customer Lifetime Value (LTV) = AOV Average Tenure

  • Gross Merchandise Value (GMV) = sum(TotalCharges)

In[319]:
data = df
# Convert 'TotalCharges' to numeric (if needed)
data["TotalCharges"] = pd.to_numeric(data["TotalCharges"], errors="coerce")

# Compute KPIs
total_subscribers = len(data)  # Total number of customers
churned_customers = data[data["Churn"] == "1"].shape[0]
active_customers = total_subscribers - churned_customers

mrr = data["MonthlyCharges"].sum()  # Monthly Recurring Revenue
aov = data["TotalCharges"].mean()   # Average Order Value
churn_rate = (churned_customers / total_subscribers) * 100  # Churn Rate
avg_tenure = data["tenure"].mean()  # Average Customer Tenure
ltv = aov * avg_tenure  # Customer Lifetime Value
gmv = data["TotalCharges"].sum()  # Gross Merchandise Value

# Display Results
print(f"Total Subscribers: {total_subscribers}")
print(f"Churn Rate: {churn_rate:.2f}%")
print(f"Monthly Recurring Revenue (MRR): ${mrr:.2f}")
print(f"Average Order Value (AOV): ${aov:.2f}")
print(f"Customer Lifetime Value (LTV): ${ltv:.2f}")
print(f"Gross Merchandise Value (GMV): ${gmv:.2f}")

In[152]:
def plot_categorical_to_target(df,categorical_values, target):
    number_of_columns = 2
    number_of_rows = math.ceil(len(categorical_values)/2)
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12, 5*number_of_rows))
    
    for index, column in enumerate(categorical_values, 1):
        ax = fig.add_subplot(number_of_rows,number_of_columns,index)
        ax = sns.countplot(x = column, data = df, hue = target, palette="Blues")
        ax.set_title(column)
    return plt.show()
In[154]:
customer_services = ["PhoneService","MultipleLines","InternetService","OnlineSecurity","OnlineBackup",
                    "DeviceProtection","TechSupport","StreamingTV","StreamingMovies"]
plot_categorical_to_target(df,customer_services, "Churn")

  • PhoneService - Customers with phone service tend to churn more than those without. However, among those with phone service, having multiple lines does not seem to impact churn rates.

  • Internet Service - Customers using Fiber Optic have the highest churn rates compared to DSL or those with no internet service. This suggests that Fiber Optic users may experience service dissatisfaction or higher costs leading to cancellations.

  • Online Security - Customers who do not subscribe to these security services tend to have higher churn rates. This indicates that providing bundled security packages may help reduce customer attrition.

  • Tech Support - A lack of tech support is associated with higher churn rates. Customers who have tech support show lower churn, suggesting that providing better technical assistance may enhance customer retention.

  • Streaming Services - Interestingly, customers with streaming services also experience higher churn, especially when they lack additional support services (online security, backup, or tech support). This may indicate that streaming users expect higher service quality and may leave if expectations are not met.

Recommendations

  • Internet Service
    Investigate customer dissatisfaction with Fiber Optic and improve service quality or pricing to reduce churn.

  • Security & Support Services
    Promote bundled services with online security, backup, and tech support to retain customers.

  • Streaming Services
    Improve the streaming experience by offering better service reliability and customer support to prevent churn.

  • Phone Services
    Assess whether phone service users have specific grievances leading to cancellations and offer retention incentives.

def histogram_plots(df, numerical_values, target):
    number_of_columns = 2
    number_of_rows = math.ceil(len(numerical_values)/2)
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12,5*number_of_rows))
    
    for index, column in enumerate(numerical_values,1):
        ax = fig.add_subplot(number_of_rows, number_of_columns, index)
        ax = sns.kdeplot(df[column][df[target]=="Yes"] ,fill = True)
        ax = sns.kdeplot(df[column][df[target]=="No"], fill = True)
        ax.set_title(column)
        ax.legend(["Churn","No Churn"], loc='upper right')
    return plt.show()

def outlier_check_boxplot(df,numerical_values):
    number_of_columns = 2
    number_of_rows = math.ceil(len(numerical_values)/2)
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12,5*number_of_rows))
    for index, column in enumerate(numerical_values, 1):
        ax = fig.add_subplot(number_of_rows, number_of_columns, index)
        ax = sns.boxplot(x = column, data = df, palette = "Blues", legend=False)
        ax.set_title(column)
    return plt.show()

feature_le = ["Partner","Dependents","PhoneService", "Churn","PaperlessBilling"]
def label_encoding(df,features):
    for i in features:
        df[i] = df[i].map({"Yes":1, "No":0})
    return df

df = label_encoding(df,feature_le)
df["gender"] = df["gender"].map({"Female":1, "Male":0})

In[386]:
# For logistic Regression
def feature_weights(X_df, classifier, classifier_name):
    weights = pd.Series(classifier.coef_[0], index = X_df.columns.values).sort_values(ascending=False)
    
    top_10_weights = weights[:10]
    plt.figure(figsize=(7,6))
    plt.title(f"{classifier_name} - Top 10 Features")
    top_10_weights.plot(kind="bar")
    
    bottom_10_weights = weights[len(weights)-10:]
    plt.figure(figsize=(7,6))
    plt.title(f"{classifier_name} - Bottom 10 Features")
    bottom_10_weights.plot(kind="bar")
    print("")
In[388]:
def confusion_matrix_plot(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, y_pred, classifier, classifier_name):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_pred,y_test)
    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm, display_labels=["No Churn", "Churn"])
    disp.plot()
    plt.title(f"Confusion Matrix - {classifier_name}")
    plt.show()
    
    print(f"Accuracy Score Test = {accuracy_score(y_pred,y_test)}")
    print(f"Accuracy Score Train = {classifier.score(X_train,y_train)}")
    return print("\n")
In[390]:
def roc_curve_auc_score(X_test, y_test, y_pred_probabilities,classifier_name):
    y_pred_prob = y_pred_probabilities[:,1]
    fpr,tpr,thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_prob)
    
    plt.plot([0,1],[0,1],"k--")
    plt.plot(fpr,tpr,label=f"{classifier_name}")
    plt.title(f"{classifier_name} - ROC Curve")
    plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
    plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
    plt.show()
    return print(f"AUC Score (ROC):{roc_auc_score(y_test,y_pred_prob)}")
In[392]:
def precision_recall_curve_and_scores(X_test, y_test, y_pred, y_pred_probabilities, classifier_name):
    y_pred_prob = y_pred_probabilities[:,1]
    precision, recall, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_pred_prob)
    plt.plot(recall,precision, label=f"{classifier_name}")
    plt.title(f"{classifier_name}-ROC Curve")
    plt.xlabel("Recall")
    plt.ylabel("Precision")
    plt.show()
    f1_score_result, auc_score = f1_score(y_test,y_pred), auc(recall,precision)
    return print(f"f1 Score : {f1_score_result} \n AUC Score (PR) : {auc_score}")

Business Recommendations
Target High TotalCharges Customers: Offer retention programs or loyalty rewards for high-spending customers.

Encourage Long-Term Contracts: Provide discounts or benefits for switching from Month-to-Month to annual contracts.

Investigate Fiber Optic Churn Causes: Analyze customer feedback on fiber optic service and address common complaints.

By implementing these strategies, businesses can reduce churn and enhance customer satisfaction.

The logistic regression model achieved a test accuracy of 80.24% and a training accuracy of 80.44%, indicating:
